I’d say the probability of google being able to connect you to people who are searching for things like ‘what is open banking’ is high. equally, if your audience hangs out on certain site on the web google can connect. Up to you to know where they hang out.
I would say, google ads work better if companies have a clear understanding of who is buying/what they are searching. Not Google’s fault, more on the company side.

Not sure about this. Customers won’t care or comprehend until they need a service that pulls them through the process. TPPs need to concentrate on creating value unlocked by open banking and the rest will fall into place.

Agreed - I think that there will be firms that are up for the cost, regulation and time needed to become a bank and there will be FinTech's using the API's but for these entities the revenue stream is very limited.

I understand this Anne but my point was that they don’t need to be a bank now that they can use bank APIs. So banks end up with the liabilities and the burden of regulation, and Facebook can replace Pingit/Paym in about a week.

Everyone underestimates what it takes to become a bank & how long it takes for regulation to be implemented e.g. I published this about PSD2 Oct 2015 - take a look and see what has changed https://www. starlingbank.com/blog/explainin g-psd2-without-tlas-tough/ …

A payment institution licence would cost Facebook approximately nothingt. It’s the bank that would remain heavily regulated. Facebook isn’t going to lend you money - it’s going to auction your leading requirement to the banks
That is the hope! Banks need to realise this.
Ok but that’s a much more natural progression for a financial services company..

Fair. I am speaking of 'banking as we know it' barebones: The minute you need a license to process payments, take deposits or issue loans, your business changes. As does your regulatory exposure.

No better way of knowing & understanding customers than their financial data. U knw where, what & how they spend in addition to when and how much they earn. Unfortunately, the banks have had this data but never had a need to do anything with it. ‘If it’s not broken, don’t fix it’
